# I/O Types:
abbreviation/file descripter number
stdin  0
stdout 1
stderr 2 
##################################################################
# Redirection:
> redirects stdout to a file (overwrites)
>> redirects stdout to a file (appends)
< redirects input from a file to a command 

& used with redirection to signal that a file descripter is being used.
2>&1 combine stderr and stdout
2>file redirect stderr to a file
##################################################################
# The Null Device:
>/dev/null redirect output to nowhere (bitbucket)

$ ls here not-here 2> /dev/null
here
$ ls here not-here > /dev/null 2>&1
$

##################################################################
example of redirection to file and then to a command:
ls > file.txt  (redirects ls output to a file)
sort < file.txt  (sorts the ls output from the file, equivalant to sort files.txt)

example of redirection to a file (2 methods):
ls -l > files.txt is the same as ls -l 1> files.txt becasue 1 is assumed for stdout redirection

example of combining redirection:
ls -l > files.txt
sort < files.txt > sorted_files.txt

example of redirecting stderr:
ls files.txt not-here 2> out.err
cat out.err  (shows the errore message which would have printed to the console)

example of redirecting stdout and stderr to different files:
ls files.txt not-here 1>out 2>out.err

example of combining stderr and stdout:
ls files.txt not-here > out.both 2>&1  (takes stderr and appends it to stdout in out.both)

example of ignoring errors by sending them to bitbucket:
ls files.txt not-here 2>/dev/null

example of sending stdout to bitbucket:
ls files.txt not-here >/dev/null

example of sending both stdout and stderr to bitbucket:
ls files.txt not-here >/dev/null 2>&1
